definition.value: Imidazole tautomer which has the migrating hydrogen at position 4.

Acridines which are substituted in any position by one or more amino groups or substituted amino groups. Note that the term 'aminoacridine' is the International Prorietary Name (INN) for 9-aminoacridine.
An amino-acid residue that occurs in procollagen.
A type of fucose-rich sulfated polysaccharide found in various species of brown algae, seaweed and sea-cucumbers.
A penicillin compound having a 6alpha-methoxy and 6beta-[2-carboxy(thiophen-3-yl)acetamido side-groups.
The D-threo-isomer of a ketoaldonic acid compound.
A primary arylamine that is aniline in which the hydrogens at the 2- and 5-positions are replaced by methyl groups. It is used in the manufacture of dyes and other chemicals.
A metabolite isolated from morels (e.g. Morchella costata) and red algae (e.g. Gracilariopsis lemaneiformis).
A ring assembly compound consisting of two flaviolin units joined by a 3,3'-linkage.
A ring assembly compound consisting of two flaviolin units joined by a 3,8'-linkage.
A ketone containing a halo group.
A haloketone in which the halogen and oxo substituents are on adjacent carbon atoms.
A ketone containing a chloro substituent.
A chloroketone in which the chlorine and oxo substituents are on adjacent carbon atoms.

A tertiary amine having one ethyl and two 3-phenylprop-1-yl groups attached to the nitrogen. An antispasmodic that acts directly on intestinal and uterine smooth muscle, it is used (particularly as the citrate salt) in the treatment of irritable bowel syndrome.
A ketone containing a bromo substituent.
A bromoketone in which the bromine and oxo substituents are on adjacent carbon atoms.
